    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-23T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-21T19:00:00-05:00" n="212"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d212">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115110/3</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Southampton</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Swalm</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Southampton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1917-03-23T11:00:00+00:00"
                            notBefore="1917-03-22T00:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">undated</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 23, 1917, 11
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Captain and crew of American submarined ship <hi rend="italic">Illinois</hi>
                    landed here from Guernsey this morning. They number 34, Americans 16. Vessel
                    bound London, Port Arthur, Tex., in ballast. Submarine sighted 20 miles north of
                    Alderney, March 18, 8 forenoon. Was shelled without warning, German submarine.
                    Weather fair, no vessels in sight, no measures taken for safety of crew and
                    towing refused. Shelling continued until crew was in their own boats. Did not
                    try to escape or resist. One man slightly wounded. Ship finally sunk by bombs
                    placed in and outside. Crew six hours in boats. Last 10 miles towed Alderney
                    motor boat. Crew sent London immediately.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Swalm</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
